WEBVTT

00:01.268 --> 00:02.568
<i> Adult mark: My father and I</i>
<i> didn't play hockey</i>

00:02.703 --> 00:04.470
<i> Or fix cars to bond.</i>

00:04.472 --> 00:06.505
<i> We read the paper.</i>
<i> [papers rustle]</i>

00:06.507 --> 00:08.307
-<i> The old man was his own</i>
<i> search engine.</i>

00:08.442 --> 00:11.176
- Oh, hell of an article here
about the feds. Scissors.

00:11.312 --> 00:13.178
<i> Adult mark: He had stacks</i>
<i> of newspaper clippings</i>

00:13.180 --> 00:15.180
<i> That he would reference</i>
<i> to write stories.</i>

00:15.182 --> 00:17.316
<i> I, too, mined the headlines</i>
<i> for fodder.</i>

00:17.318 --> 00:20.318
- [chuckles] hell of a good
joke in this drabble cartoon.

00:20.454 --> 00:22.054
<i> Scissors?</i>

00:22.056 --> 00:25.190
<i> Adult mark: Mom and pop got</i>
<i> the news in a different way.</i>

00:25.192 --> 00:29.127
Mary: Oh, jean got a cab
to work today. Hmph!

00:29.196 --> 00:31.396
I heard she had a date
with an oil rig worker.

00:31.398 --> 00:33.331
I bet she left her car downtown
last night,

00:33.367 --> 00:35.133
And we all know
what that means.

00:35.202 --> 00:37.202
- Hey, mail truck stopped
at the o'connors.

00:37.204 --> 00:38.871
What's the date? 5th?
- Mm...

00:38.873 --> 00:40.472
- It's not the old age pension.

00:40.541 --> 00:43.442
Ah... Welfare cheques are out.
[chuckles]

00:43.577 --> 00:45.677
- Poor john o'conner's been
out of work for months.

00:45.679 --> 00:48.547
He says it's his leg,
but you know what I heard?

00:48.616 --> 00:50.816
It's his elbow.
- Hmm. [chuckles]

00:50.885 --> 00:53.518
- Hey, mark, stop playing
with your father.

00:53.554 --> 00:55.620
You need to start practicing
for your school play audition,

00:55.689 --> 00:57.556
Hmm?
- Audition?

00:57.625 --> 01:00.526
What play are you doin'?
- It's the easter carol.

01:00.528 --> 01:02.527
It's the story
of the resurrection, told--

01:02.596 --> 01:04.229
- Through the eyes
of the innkeeper

01:04.298 --> 01:06.231
Who catered the last supper.

01:06.233 --> 01:07.966
[laughs] they're still doin'
that.

01:07.968 --> 01:10.436
- You know it?
- Know it? I was in it!

01:10.571 --> 01:12.771
I played hamar, the innkeeper.

01:12.906 --> 01:15.641
My teacher said that
I was spectacular.

01:15.776 --> 01:18.243
- Yeah. You were a spectacle,
you mean.

01:18.245 --> 01:21.212
That play was god awful.
[mail thumps]

01:21.248 --> 01:23.482
- What part are you trying
out for, mark?

01:23.551 --> 01:25.050
- Hamar, the innkeeper.

01:25.052 --> 01:27.386
- [loud thud] same part!
[paper thumps lightly]

01:27.521 --> 01:29.321
I could help you
to your run lines.

01:29.390 --> 01:32.390
That's what we actors call
rehearsing.

01:32.426 --> 01:34.259
<i> Adult mark: The old man</i>
<i> was interested in me!</i>

01:34.261 --> 01:35.927
<i> This was unprecedented.</i>

01:35.996 --> 01:37.329
- That'd be great.

01:37.464 --> 01:39.865
- Chip off the old block.
[paper flaps]

01:40.000 --> 01:41.466
<i>Pop: Oh, they're not cheques!</i>

01:41.502 --> 01:44.536
Oh no, it's a package!
- What?

01:44.671 --> 01:46.805
Now, why on earth would
they be gettin' a package?

01:46.807 --> 01:49.807
- Oh, well, mary, make us
a cup o' tea, luv.

01:49.944 --> 01:52.878
Looks like I'll be eating
at the window today.

01:53.013 --> 01:56.748
- First thing you gotta know,
acting is pretending.

01:56.750 --> 01:59.284
You might hear people say
that acting is listening.

01:59.320 --> 02:02.020
Don't listen,
'cause that'll throw you off.

02:02.156 --> 02:04.489
- So, that's a table for
thirteen, no reservation,

02:04.525 --> 02:06.558
And you all wanna sit
on one side?

02:06.594 --> 02:09.027
Well, I'll see what I can do,
but I'm, hmph,

02:09.096 --> 02:10.395
I'm no miracle worker!

02:10.531 --> 02:13.298
- Good! Good! Although try it
a little louder!

02:13.300 --> 02:15.634
You really ha' to project
to your audience.

02:15.636 --> 02:18.303
Pretend that there's a deaf old
man in the back of the room.

02:18.305 --> 02:20.105
- What?
- Nothing.

02:20.174 --> 02:23.241
Now, stand with your feet at
quarter to and quarter after

02:23.310 --> 02:25.210
To open yourself up
for your audience.

02:25.345 --> 02:27.078
And it's always a good idea

02:27.148 --> 02:29.715
To address your audience
with a little wave.

02:29.850 --> 02:32.651
Say, "hello, audience!"

02:32.653 --> 02:35.721
- Hello, audience!
Goodbye, moron!

02:35.856 --> 02:38.724
This play has always sucked.
[footsteps recede]

02:38.726 --> 02:40.992
- Never listen to the critics.

02:41.061 --> 02:43.462
Don't mind him.
He's just jealous.

02:43.597 --> 02:47.065
We never had a special bond
like you and I have.

02:47.134 --> 02:48.866
- [sighs happily]

02:48.903 --> 02:50.936
- I'm so proud of you, son,

02:51.005 --> 02:52.837
And I know you're not gonna
let me down.

02:52.907 --> 02:55.073
Now, get in position,

02:55.142 --> 02:57.542
Shoulders back,

02:57.545 --> 02:59.544
And... Hello, audience!

02:59.547 --> 03:01.213
- Hello, audience!

03:01.215 --> 03:02.614
- Very good.
- Oh.

03:02.650 --> 03:05.116
- Feel the magic in the air?

03:05.186 --> 03:07.219
- Yeah.
- That's show business.

03:07.221 --> 03:09.388
- [exhales sharply,
then chuckles]

03:09.390 --> 03:12.357
- Oh, your timing's off
by a good five years, my luv.

03:12.359 --> 03:15.293
Well, yes, I'm sure.
Elizabeth critch died in--

03:15.362 --> 03:17.395
- [panicked] dear god!
Give me that!

03:17.431 --> 03:20.899
Yes, hello? Uh, yes,
this is patrick critch.

03:20.901 --> 03:23.301
You were speaking to my wife,
elizabeth.

03:23.370 --> 03:26.938
Sadly, her mind has gone.

03:27.007 --> 03:29.675
I know, luv, I know.
It's a very sad situation,

03:29.810 --> 03:32.844
But as you can see,
she's very much alive...

03:32.846 --> 03:35.213
[cord rattles,
struggling grunts]

03:35.216 --> 03:37.282
And stronger than
she would appear.

03:37.417 --> 03:39.150
Yeah--oh, oh, oh my god!

03:39.220 --> 03:41.519
She's wandering towards
the highway, I better go!

03:41.555 --> 03:43.388
[handset clanks with force]

03:44.458 --> 03:46.858
- Nanny is dead.
- [grunts]

03:46.860 --> 03:49.394
My darling elizabeth
will always live on

03:49.396 --> 03:51.263
Close to my heart.

03:51.265 --> 03:53.865
More specifically,
her pension will also live on

03:53.934 --> 03:56.000
In my bank account,

03:56.036 --> 03:59.571
Because I didn't report her
as dead.

03:59.573 --> 04:02.607
- Oh my god!
- Oh, what's the big deal?!

04:02.610 --> 04:04.542
The government ha' got
plenty of money.

04:04.612 --> 04:07.479
They didn't notice...
Until recently.

04:07.614 --> 04:10.882
- Is this the first time
the cra has called here?

04:11.018 --> 04:13.084
- Yeah-- what do you mean,
today?

04:13.086 --> 04:14.552
- Jesus in the jungle!

04:15.589 --> 04:17.322
You will put an end to this,

04:17.457 --> 04:19.424
Or I will reunite you
with your wife

04:19.426 --> 04:22.628
Sooner than you thought!

04:22.763 --> 04:24.429
[footsteps recede]

04:24.431 --> 04:28.600
♪♪♪

04:28.669 --> 04:30.268
<i>[plastic hockey sticks thwap]</i>

04:30.304 --> 04:32.504
